04888nam a22009135i 9783110352962DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20142014gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2014031439  a(OCoLC)979585511  a97831103529627 a10.1515/97831103529622doi  a(DE-B1597)335912  a(OCoLC)898769850  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aBS1430.52b.K38 2014 4aBS1430.52b.K38 2014 7aREL0060302bisacsh04a223/.2062231 aKartje, John , eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWisdom Epistemology in the Psalter :b A Study of Psalms 1, 73, 90, and 107 /cJohn Kartje. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (216 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBeihefte zur Zeitschrift für die alttestamentliche Wissenschaft ,x0934-2575 ;v4720 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe present a comparative epistemological analysis of the wisdom motifs in Psalms 1, 73, 90, and 107. These texts were selected on the basis of their epistemological content (each confronts the relationship between virtue and prosperity), and their canonical placement within the Psalter (each begins one of the Psalter’s five “Books”). We explore the implications of their respective epistemological features for our understanding of the canonical structure of the Psalter.After developing a diagnostic method for the identification and analysis of the epistemological features within a biblical text, we apply it to each of the four psalms, and discuss their epistemological qualities with respect to their canonical placement in the Psalter.We find that an epistemic progression develops across the canonical ordering of the four psalms. While the psalmists are increasingly forthright in acknowledging the moral paradox that the righteous often suffer, while the wicked can prosper, they engage this paradox with ever more sophisticated responses. Although Yhwh is ultimately the source of all wisdom, human beings can facilitate their acquisition of knowledge by seeking him out intentionally, by questioning him directly, and by observing him with a heart focused on learning.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aKnowledge, Theory of (Religion) 0aKnowledge, Theory of (Religion). 0aWisdom. 4aEpistemologie. 4aPsalmen. 4aWeisheit. 7aRELIGION / Bible / Biography / Old Testament.2bisacsh  aCanonical.  aEpistemology.  aPsalter.  aWisdom.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Complete English Language 2000-2014 PART1z978311023857008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Theology and Religious Studies 2000-2014 (EN)z978311023854908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Theology and Religious Studies 2000 - 2014z9783110638165oZDB-23-GTR08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Complete Package 2014z9783110369526oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theology, Religion, Judaism 2014z9783110370409oZDB-23-DGF0 cEPUBz97831103834540 cprintz978311035053140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311035296240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110352962423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110352962/original  a978-3-11-023854-9  DGBA Backlist Theology and Religious Studies 2000-2014 (EN)c2000d2014  a978-3-11-023857-0  DGBA Backlist Complete English Language 2000-2014 PART1c2000d2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGFb2014  aZDB-23-DGGb2014  aZDB-23-GTRc2000d2014